[2]
Date: Thu, 06 Mar 1997 08:36:23 -0600
From: Tam Garland <TGARLAND@CVM.TAMU.EDU>
Another side of the issue is to consider why we would want genetically
identical individuals (rodents or whatever) for pharmaceutical/ chemical
testing when we would then not understand the adverse side affects or even
be able to develop an appropriate treatment for a genetically diverse
population.
Even if there were genetically engineered races of people, what about those
that are genetically diverse? Would that group of people/animals no longer
benefit from treatments or would there even be any existing treatments [for
such genetically diverse people-mod. pc]? Would we be able to recognize a
disease/illness in a biologically diverse population if we persist in
studying it in a genetically homogenous population?
I think that these and a multitude of other questions concerning medical
issues for both human and animal populations should be carefully considered
before any cloning is really unleashed on an unsuspecting world. This
smacks a lot of how Hitler wanted to take over the world. Are we simply
providing some genius/lunatic with the ability?
--
Tam Garland DVM,PhD
TGARLAND@CVM.TAMU.EDU
